: center;"><span>Third</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p dir=3D"ltr"><=
span>We can easily define these operations using two Boolean variables. </s=
pan></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Let's take two Boolean variables A and B that =
can have any of the two values 0 or 1, i.e., they can be either OFF or ON. =
Then these operations are explained as,</span></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Desktop=
_InContent_ATF_728x280" style=3D"text-align: center; margin: 10px 0px;"></d=
iv><h3 id=3D"negation-or-not-operation" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Neg=
ation or NOT Operation</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Using the </span><a =
href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/digital-logic/not-gate/" target=3D"_b=
lank" rel=3D"noopener"><span>NOT</span></a><span> operation reverse the val=
ue of the Boolean variable from 0 to 1 or vice-versa. This can be understoo=
d as:</span></p><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>If A =3D 1, then usin=
g NOT operation we have (A)' =3D 0</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>If A =
=3D 0, then using the NOT operation we have (A)' =3D 1</span></li><li value=
=3D"3"><span>We also represent the negation operation as ~A, i.e if A =3D 1=
, ~A =3D 0</span></li></ul></blockquote><h3 id=3D"conjunction-or-and-operat=
ion" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Conjunction or AND Operation</span></h=
3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Using the</span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks=
.org/digital-logic/and-gate/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span> AND=
</span></a><span> operation satisfies the condition if both the values of t=
he individual variables are true, and if any of the values is false, then t=
his operation gives a negative result. This can be understood as,</span></p=
><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>If A =3D True, B =3D True, then A . =
B =3D True</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>If A =3D True, B =3D False, Or =
A =3D false, B =3D True, then A . B =3D False</span></li><li value=3D"3"><s=
pan>If A =3D False, B =3D False, then A . B =3D False</span></li></ul></blo=
ckquote><h3 id=3D"disjunction-or-operation" style=3D"text-align:left"><span=
>Disjunction (OR) Operation</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Using the </spa=
n><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/digital-logic/or-gate/" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span>OR</span></a><span> operation satisfies =
the condition if any value of the individual variables is true; it only giv=
es a negative result if both the values are false. This can be understood a=
s,</span></p><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>If A =3D True, B =3D Tru=
e, then A + B =3D True</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>If A =3D True, B =
=3D False, Or A =3D false, B =3D True, then A + B =3D True</span></li><li v=
alue=3D"3"><span>If A =3D False, B =3D False, then A + B =3D False</span></=
li></ul></blockquote><h2 id=3D"boolean-algebra-table" style=3D"text-align:l=
eft"><span>Boolean Algebra Table (Extended)</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span=
