pan></td><td><span>Returns false if at least one input is true.</span></td>=
</tr><tr><th><b><strong>XNOR Operation</strong></b></th><td><span>=E2=86=94=
</span></td><td><span>Returns true if both inputs are equal.</span></td></t=
r></tbody></table><h2 id=3D"boolean-expression-and-variables" style=3D"text=
-align:left"><span>Boolean Expression and Variables</span></h2><p dir=3D"lt=
r" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Boolean expression is an expression=
 that produces a Boolean value when evaluated, i.e., it produces either a t=
rue value or a false value. Whereas Boolean variables are variables that st=
ore Boolean numbers. </span></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Incontent_2" style=3D"tex=
t-align: center; margin: 10px 0px;"></div><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>P + Q =3D R =
is a Boolean expression in which P, Q, and R are Boolean variables that can=
 only store two values: 0 and 1.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Thus, we ca=
n say that statements using Boolean variables and operating on Boolean oper=
ations are Boolean Expressions. Some examples of Boolean expressions are,</=
span></p><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>A + B =3D True</span></li><l=
i value=3D"2"><span>A . B =3D True</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>(A)' =
=3D False</span></li></ul></blockquote><h2 id=3D"truth-tablesin-boolean-alg=
ebra" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Truth Tables</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr=
" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>A truth table represents all the com=
binations of input values and outputs in a tabular manner. All the possibil=
ities of the input and output are shown in it ,and hence the name truth tab=
le. In logic problems, truth tables are commonly used to represent various =
cases. T or 1 denotes 'True' &amp; F or 0 denotes 'False' in the truth tabl=
e.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: left;"><b><str=
ong>Number of Rows in Truth Table =3D 2 </strong></b><b><sup><strong>n</str=
ong></sup></b></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>where </span><b><strong>n</stro=
ng></b><span> is the number of Boolean variables used.</span></li></ul></bl=
ockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Example: Draw the truth table of the con=
ditions A + B and A . B ,where A and B are Boolean variables.</strong></b><=
/p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span=
