<h2 id=3D"laws-for-boolean-algebra" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Laws fo=
r Boolean Algebra</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>These are the rules we us=
e to simplify logical expressions and design efficient circuits.</span></p>=
<h3 id=3D"identity-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>1. Identity Law</sp=
an></h3><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>In the Boolean =
Algebra, we have identity elements for both AND(.) and OR(+) operations. Th=
e identity law states that in Boolean algebra, we have such variables that,=
 on operating with the  AND and OR operations we get the same result, i.e.<=
/span></p><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>A + 0 =3D A</span></li><li =
value=3D"2"><span>A.1 =3D A</span></li></ul></blockquote><h3 id=3D"commutat=
ive-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>2. Commutative Law</span></h3><p d=
ir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Binary variables in Boolean=
 Algebra follow the commutative law. This law states that operating Boolean=
 variables A and B is similar to operating Boolean variables B and A. That =
is,</span></p><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>A. B =3D B. A</span></l=
i><li value=3D"2"><span>A + B =3D B + A</span></li></ul></blockquote><h3 id=
=3D"associative-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>3. Associative Law</sp=
an></h3><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Associative law=
 states that the order of performing Boolean operator is illogical as their=
 result is always the same. This can be understood as,</span></p><blockquot=
e><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>( A . B ) . C =3D A . ( B . C )</span></li><li =
value=3D"2"><span>( A + B ) + C =3D A + ( B + C)</span></li></ul></blockquo=
te><h3 id=3D"distributive-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>4. Distribut=
ive Law</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Bool=
ean Variables also follow the distributive law, and the expression for the =
Distributive law is given as:</span></p><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><sp=
an>A . ( B + C) =3D (A . B) + (A . C)</span></li></ul></blockquote><h3 id=
=3D"inversion-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>5. Inversion Law</span><=
/h3><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Inversion law is th=
e unique law of Boolean algebra that states, the complement of the compleme=
nt of any number is the number itself.</span></p><blockquote><ul><li value=
=3D"1"><span>(A')' =3D A</span></li></ul></blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=
=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Apart from these other laws are mentioned b=
elow:</span></p><h3 id=3D"and-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>6. AND L=
aw</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>AND law o=
f the Boolean algebra uses AND operator and the AND law is,</span></p><bloc=
kquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>A . 0 =3D 0</span></li><li value=3D"2"><sp=
an>A . 1 =3D A</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>A . A =3D A</span></li></ul=
></blockquote><h3 id=3D"or-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>7. OR Law</=
span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>OR law of the=
 Boolean algebra uses OR operator and the OR law is,</span></p><blockquote>=
<ul><li value=3D"1"><span>A  + 0 =3D A</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>A +=
 1 =3D 1</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>A + A =3D A</span></li></ul></blo=
ckquote><h3 id=3D"8-complement-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>8.=
 Complement Law</strong></b></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The </span><b><strong=
>Complement Law</strong></b><span> states that a variable ORed with its com=
plement is always 1, and a variable ANDed with its complement is always 0.<=
/span></p><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>A + A' =3D 1</span></li><li=
 value=3D"2"><span>A . A' =3D 0</span></li></ul></blockquote><h3 id=3D"9-do=
mination-law" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>9. Domination Law</stron=
g></b></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The </span><b><strong>Domination Law</stron=
g></b><span> states that any variable ORed with 1 will always be 1, and any=
 variable ANDed with 0 will always be 0.</span></p><blockquote><ul><li valu=
e=3D"1"><span>A + 1 =3D 1</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>A . 0 =3D 0</spa=
n></li></ul></blockquote><h3 id=3D"10-double-negation-law" style=3D"text-al=
ign:left"><span>10. Double Negation Law</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The=
 </span><b><strong>Double Negation Law</strong></b><span> states that the c=
omplement of the complement of a variable is the variable itself.</span></p=
><blockquote><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>(A')' =3D A</span></li></ul></blockq=
